# K = 1
data = np.hstack([x, y])
xp = np.linspace(-30, 30, 100).reshape(-1, 1)
yp = []

for i in range(len(xp)):
    
    dist_and_index = []
    
    for j, pts in enumerate(data):
        dist = 0
        dist = np.sqrt(np.sum((np.subtract(pts[:-1], xp[i]))**2))

        dist_and_index.append((dist, j))

    sort_dist_and_index = sorted(dist_and_index)

    knn_dist_and_index = sort_dist_and_index[:1]

    knn_labels = [data[j][1] for dist, j in knn_dist_and_index]
    
    knn_avg = np.mean(knn_labels)
    
    yp.append(knn_avg)

from collections import Counter
res = 0.01
[X1gr, X2gr] = np.meshgrid(np.arange(-1.5,1.5,res), np.arange(-1.5,1.5,res))
Xp = np.hstack([X1gr.reshape(-1,1), X2gr.reshape(-1,1)]) ## 
for i in range(len(Xp)):
    t = np.sqrt(np.sum((np.subtract(Xp[i], X))**2, axis=1)).reshape(-1, 1) ## Euclidian distance
    q = np.hstack([t, y]) 
    sort_p = sorted(q.tolist()) ## Sort the distance
    knnCLF = sort_p[:1] # Select the top highest dataset
    knnCLF = np.array(knnCLF)  
    knnCLF_label = knnCLF[:,1] ##
    yp.append(Counter(knnCLF_label).most_common(1)[0][0])

Problem 3

Look at the following training set for a decision tree that classifies names as either location or person names:


1) Calculate the disorder of attribute 1.

2) Calculate the disorder of attribute 2.

3) Which attribute is more useful, attribute 1 or attribute 2 ? and Why?

$$\begin{align*} D & = -\frac{l}{T} \log_2 \frac{l}{T} - \frac{p}{T} \log_2 \frac{p}{T} \qquad \text{where }\; l: \text{location}, \; p: \text{person},\; T: \text{Total}\\ \\ \end{align*} $$$$Q(\text{test}) = \sum D(\text{set}) \times \frac{\text{# of samples in set}}{\text{# of samples in all sets}}$$

1) Calculate disorder of attribute 1.

$$\begin{align*} D_{\text{attribute1 yes}} & = -\frac{3}{6} \log_2 \frac{3}{6} - \frac{3}{6} \log_2 \frac{3}{6} = 1\\ \\ D_{\text{attribute1 no}} & = -\frac{1}{3} \log_2 \frac{1}{3} - \frac{2}{3} \log_2 \frac{2}{3} = 0.9183 \end{align*} $$

2) Calculate disorder of attribute 2.

$$\begin{align*} D_{\text{attribute2 yes}} & = -\frac{4}{4} \log_2 \frac{4}{4} - \frac{0}{4} \log_2 \frac{0}{4} = 0\\ \\ D_{\text{attribute2 no}} & = -\frac{0}{5} \log_2 \frac{0}{5} - \frac{5}{5} \log_2 \frac{5}{5} = 0 \end{align*} $$


3) Which attribute is more useful, attribute 1 or attribute 2 Why?

$$ \begin{align*} Q_{\text{attribute1}} &= 1\times\frac{6}{9} + 0.9183\times\frac{3}{9} = 0.973\\ Q_{\text{attribute2}} &= 0\times\frac{4}{9} + 0\times\frac{5}{9} = 0\\\\ Q_{\text{attribute1}} &> Q_{\text{attribute2}}\\\\ \therefore \;&\text{attribute 2 is more useful.} \end{align*} $$

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

X = np.hstack((data1, data2, data3, data4))
X = np.asmatrix(X)
X = X.T
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = 4, random_state = 0)
kmeans.fit(X)


c1x = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 0,0])
c1y = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 0,1])
c2x = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 1,0])
c2y = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 1,1])
c3x = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 2,0])
c3y = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 2,1])
c4x = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 3,0])
c4y = np.mean(X[kmeans.labels_ == 3,1])

c1 = [c1x, c1y]
c2 = [c2x, c2y]

plt.plot(X[kmeans.labels_ == 3,0],X[kmeans.labels_ == 3,1], 'c.', label = 'class 4')

from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

m = img.shape[0]
n = img.shape[1]
X = img.reshape(m*n, 3)

k = 6
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = k, random_state = 0)
kmeans.fit(X)
Out[20]:
KMeans(algorithm='auto', copy_x=True, init='k-means++', max_iter=300,
    n_clusters=6, n_init=10, n_jobs=None, precompute_distances='auto',
    random_state=0, tol=0.0001, verbose=0)
In[21]:
X_clustered = np.zeros([m*n,3])

for i in range(k): 
    X_clustered[np.where(kmeans.labels_ == i)] = kmeans.cluster_centers_[i]
In[22]:
plt.figure(figsize = (8,8))
plt.imshow(X_clustered.reshape(m, n, 3).astype('uint8'))
plt.axis('off')
plt.show()

for i in range(1, 8):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters = i, random_state = 0).fit(X)
    cost.append(abs(kmeans.score(X_clustered)))
    print(i)
